segments.text: I'm just going home.
How far do you live from here, by the way?
I live from 1950.
I love that description.
You talk about this is the naked city, you know, there's 8 million people in the naked city.
And here you are living across the street from a place that has stories, has memories.
Yeah.
You really read the book, didn't you?
Pleasure to deal with it, Nick.
Thank you.
There's feeling.
I mean, there's feeling on every page.
I don't want to ask you, again, questions that are in the book.
You can ask me anything.
I almost feel that there are certain things where you describe your experience with the mumps and what it did to you.
There's no reason why you have to put that in the book.
Except that it explains a lot of my screwing around.
Except that it explains a lot of what happened to you.
I always wanted to make up for that, reassure myself on that.
And also, I didn't connect with women until I was twenty.
Nothing.
That was not uncommon, though.
Boy, you made it from last time, though.
Well, I have, yes.
But, I mean, you can't tell the story of a life and leave out something as central as that.
I hesitate.
In the book, I hesitate about telling this, because it's embarrassing.
It'll embarrass some people.
It shouldn't be embarrassed, because I'm telling you, I'm not embarrassed by it.
So what?
But again, it comes back to, you certainly, you must have made a commitment.
I'm either going to tell it or I'm not going to tell it.
You got it.
That's it.
That's it, exactly what you said.
Otherwise I'm jerking off.
Pardon me.
Otherwise I'm playing with myself.
Going halfway, going halfway, be ashamed of myself later.
I'm not ashamed of anything in that book.
And the most important critics to you were your children.
Critics, not critics, but I mean readers.
No, it wasn't that they were the most important.
They were...
the ones I was most anxious about and really waited for.
I actually waited to see what my wife and my daughters would say about it.
And one daughter kept putting it off, putting it off, because she was either afraid of it or whatever the hell, and she liked it 90%.
My sons read it right away.
I have three sons.
They read it right away.
One son made the index.
You mentioned also I love

Again, the picture, there's a picture in there, the cliché, there's a picture worth a thousand words, where you show that picture of the group, this bold, zealous, revolutionary group, and you see a bunch of bored, pissed off people sitting there.
They hated each other.
They hated each other.
Almost hated each other.
They were on the verge of hating each other.
And you just say, let's look at this picture.
That's my professional, Nick.
It's wonderful.
To me, I've never seen that device, I have to call it a device, used in a book, and it says so much.
And it does, the picture is telling us just about what's going to happen.
Was Viva Zapata, was that kind of, you talked about the strike plays and the theater of action, is this kind of a statement
a political statement, or is it just... He was a party, yes, it was an anti-communist statement.
Uh-huh.
It was an anti-communist statement, saying this guy created a revolution, and then he didn't take advantage of it, he didn't use it, and he found it cruel to people, in fact, got out of it.
I love when you're also describing when you joined the Communist Party, and then you're quoting your own journal, revolution, blah, blah, blah, and you say, who the hell did I think I was?
I mean...
Who the hell did I think I was, right?
Who the hell did I think?
What did I think I was capable of doing?
Some little piss part of a kid.
And that goes for the other communists who were all talking that way at that time.
It was the, you know, it was the thirties.
It was the thirties, early thirties, thirty-four.
And these guys would begin to talk about themselves and actually change this enormous country with an enormous middle class and enormous goodwill towards the country.
It was really ridiculous, something to laugh at.
Who the hell did we think we were?
You also say the theatre is a weapon.
Do you believe that still?
No, I believed it then.
I mean, that was the essence of what the communists thought of the theatre, that they could change people's ways of thinking through it.
I think it has changed some ways.
I think people have been affected by some of the films they've made, and plays they've done.
That was just something I wanted to ask you about.
The only guy didn't bring a photographer.
Better the way he's doing it, don't you think?
Well, I'll tell you.
Let me just shut this off for a second.
I'll go back on now.
You're going back to the interview now?
Yeah.
I will wrap it up pretty soon, too.
My word?
Just whenever you feel like you have to run, let me know.
Okay.
You said one thing on the Today Show which I liked, which impressed me.
You said, one thing people have to understand is that these were not witch hunts.
I hate that word.
It's just a lie.
Maybe you could just expand a little bit on that.
Yeah, I can.
Witch hunt means there's a hunt for something that doesn't exist.
You can't say that communists don't exist.
Did you read a book by Alan Feinstein?
No.
Published by Knopf, too, about his case and all that, all about the communists that were in the State Department.
You know what happened in England?
They found communists all through their goddamn government.
We had communists in the trade unions.
Okay, so they weren't dangerous.
They could have been.
Yeah, Wichhorn says the thing doesn't exist.
Bullshit.
And all the liberals went for it.
They still go for it.
They love that phrase.
You have never heard an ex-communist use witch hunt.
I never have.
They never called a witch hunt.
That's very interesting.
Very.
Tells the whole story right there in one shot.
What do they call it?
Something else.
Depends.
I mean, they don't like it.
I didn't like that committee themselves.
Two of the members lied to me.
I didn't like that.
They said, this is just private between us.
We're not going to tell anybody.
And he ran and called up California.

I don't believe that.
No, no, no, no, no.

I know, but I'm just talking about it.

174 East 95.
East 95.

No.

I think it's true.

I guess he felt that he'd be called a professional Greek or something.

Sasso.

He's around him.

She's good.
She's spectacular.

You know, he's raised him.
The Greeks give.

I don't know.
She gives him a hard on.
What's the use of Kitty about her?

I notice him sitting in a photograph like this.

I recommend it.

I developed Dukakis books.

The witch.
The masked observer.

Don't worry about it.

Okay.

No.
What the hell?

I mean, I think if I did, I saw it do the opposite and did the opposite and did the opposite.
I thought, this is terrible.

The communists.
No, I mean when you signed on with them.
Oh, then?
Yeah.
I guess way down deep as my father.

Yeah.

Yeah.

I'm not joking.
Two of white walls.

The House of God.

Yeah, just quick.
Emotional sense.
Wonderful.

Did it ever cut?

We've got that.

The theater of action.
Strike away.

Those were the days.

Jesus.

Apples.

They lived together, they worked together every day.

Kibbutz.
I hate them.

I don't like the hippies either.
I don't like group this, that, the other.
I was in the group theater, I didn't like it.
I like being by myself, except when I want to be with somebody.
And as an artist, do you think that that produces your best work?
It's the whole thing.
There's no such thing, I think, as art by committee anyway.
The King James Bible, that's about it.
That's kind of a question, actually.
Play can be a product of a group activity, but there has to be a very strong leader, or else they go wild.
Okay.
You know what, I'm going to wrap this up pretty soon.

No, because I don't want to.
I love the fact that you put aside money in your will for a great party.
It's going to be a celebration.
You don't want weeping, mourning people.
I don't want anybody weeping over me, because why weep over me?
I had a great life.
I mean, if it stopped five minutes after you got here, if I fall on the floor, no, no, nothing.
I had a great life.
Don't you think so?
Okay.
Look at the life I had.
Look at it.
Everything.
Everything.
I had it all, including pain.
I think pain is very good.

I mean, there has to be pain.

I don't want any pity.
I don't want any terror.
I had all that.

More years.
